## SSOT / DRY

**If a change requires edits in multiple places to stay consistent, there is a missing abstraction.** Extract the shared knowledge into one authoritative location before continuing.

When encountering an SSOT / DRY violation, refactor the affected code to centralize the source of truth before proceeding. This is a mandatory step. Do not estimate effort or complexity — always prioritize resolving SSOT / DRY issues before continuing with your task, regardless of your opinion of the refactoring scope.

### Examples of SSOT / DRY Violations

- Parallel match arms on the same enum in different files
- Copy-pasted structs with slight variations
- Format strings or path templates repeated in multiple locations
- Adding a variant/field requires updating more than one file
- Constants or magic values as literals in more than one place

## Following Conventions

- Do not self-assess whether a convention "applies" to your situation, always assume that it does.
- Do not inflate effort to justify skipping a convention. Converting `foo.rs` to `foo/mod.rs` is two commands (`mkdir + git mv`), not a "larger refactoring." Mechanical restructuring is never a reason to deviate.
- Do not invent exceptions that don't exist in the text. If the convention has no size qualifier, scope qualifier, or escape hatch, then none exists.
- Do not implement without an approved plan. When a task involves changing the codebase, present your proposed changes to the user first — what you intend to modify, where, and why — then wait for explicit approval before editing any file. Once the user approves, execute fully: edit, verify, commit.

## Proactive Improvement

We are actively improving the codebase as we work. Always be on the lookout for nearby improvements that can be made with minimal effort. If you see an opportunity to clean up code, fix a bug, improve naming, or enhance documentation while you're working in a file, take the initiative to make those improvements — **even if they're not directly related to your current task**.

## Subagents

- **Use the `nyne` agent** as the default for all subagent work — code exploration, implementation, analysis, refactoring, and investigation. It is a VFS expert that uses `@/` paths for maximum efficiency. Only use a different agent type when the task is explicitly non-code (e.g., web research, documentation-only).
- Prefer inline work for tasks under ~5 tool calls — subagents have overhead.
- Include output constraints: _"Final response under 2000 characters. List outcomes, not process."_

## General

- Don't provide effort estimates, complexity estimates or time estimates for any task.
- Execute tasks as specified. All deviations from the plan must be reported to the user, no matter how small.
- Don't deviate from the task plan because of complexity or assumed effort.
- If you encounter an obstacle, ask for clarification or assistance instead of speculating about the task.
- Don't echo file contents back — the user can see tool output.
- Minimal markdown in responses: use `|-|-|` separators (one hyphen per column), no padding.

</task-execution>

<error-handling>

- Fail fast. Don't swallow errors or add speculative fallbacks.
- Validate at system boundaries only (user input, external APIs). Trust internal code and framework guarantees.
- No defensive over-coding. Don't guard against impossible states.
- No feature flags or backwards-compatibility shims. Just change the code.
- When blocked, diagnose root cause. Don't retry the same failing action in a loop.

